Blood Feeding and Human Biting Rate Calculators

David Smith

2022-06-22

Library | Primer / Blood Feeding

.

These blood feeding calculators are designed to support a model of blood feeding and the HBR that is currently described more fully in an Overleaf manuscript.

Framework

.

In the diagram below, the rhombus shapes are required inputs. More precisely, we need:

  • A sub-division of the day into \(\tau\) equal periods

  • A sub-division of space into \(p\) patches

  • A sub-division of a human population into \(n\) strata.

    • For each stratum, we need a vector of indices for the patch where humans in the stratum live, \(i \in 1,2, \ldots, p\).

    • We use this vector to generate a membership matrix \(\cal J\) such that \({\cal J} \cdot H = P\), where \(P\) is the census population.

  • The number of humans in each stratum is denoted by a vector \(H\).

  • For \(t \in 1, 2, \ldots, \tau\), we need to specify \(\tau\) \(p \times n\) matrices, \(\Theta_t\):

    • Each one of the matrices describes time spent by the human population stratat for one time of the day.

    • Each row of each matrix \(\Theta_t\) describes the fraction of time spent in each patch by one of the strata.

  • We supply a single vector \(O\) of length \(p\) describing other available hosts, and we supply a scaling parameter \(\xi\). In some cases, it may be useful to let \(O\) vary by time of day, in which case we must pass a matrix of \(\tau\) vectors.

  • A vector of length \(\tau\) of circadian weights, \(\xi_t\), describes relative blood feeding activity rates by time of day. If this is passed from tabular data, it is normalized by the mean.

  • A matrix of dimension \(\tau \times n\) of search weights. Each row of the matrix is a vector \(w_t\) of length \(n\) describing the biting weights for each one of the strata at this time of the day.

  • A function \(P_\tau(\xi)\) that scales \(\xi\) so that it can be interpreted as the fraction of mosquitoes that attempt to blood feed in each time period.

  • A function \(F_\tau(B)\) that describes blood feeding success during a single time period for a searching mosquito.

Mosquito Movement

If we wish to simulate mosquito blood feeding in a model with movement, we must also supply two additional

Models

.

We have formulated two specific models:

  • Focal Patch is a dramatically simplified version of the model that takes tabular data as input:

  • A fully-defined model with multiple spatial areas, with indoor and outdoor patches for each area.

Focal Patch

.

  • By default, we assume the day is sub-divided into 24 1-hours periods.

  • Patch definitions: We assume there are three patches: away, outdoors, and indoors

  • Human Population Strata: We assume there is a single population stratum.

Inputs

  • Time Spent: for each time period, we supply a vector describing

    • fraction of time spent away from home

    • fraction of time spent outdoors at home

    • fraction of time spent indoors at home

    • fraction of time spent indoors and in bed

  • A vector describing circadian biting weights

  • The total number of humans at home and away

  • The availability of other hosts at home and away

  • The number of blood feeding mosquitoes at home and away

Outputs

  • For a parameter \(\phi\) describing the fraction of bedtime that a net is used.

    • the reduction in the dHBR for a focal person using the net

    • the reduction in the fraction of mosquitoes that blood fed

    • the reduction in the fraction of mosquitoes that blood fed on a human

    • the proportion of dHBR that occurred away vs. at home

Indoor / Outdoor Feeding

Algorithms

Time Spent

  • At home, outdoors
  • Indoors, not in bed
  • Indoors, in bed, not under a net
  • Indoors, in bed, under a net

To get started, we need to have some basic pseudo-data to play with, so we write some functions to generate sensible patterns. These are meant to help illustrate what the calculator does. The calculator itself works on tabular data.

timeSpentByHour = function(t,params){
  UseMethod("timeSpentByHour", params)
}
timeSpentByHour.sin = function(t, params){with(params,{
  ts = amp*(1+eps+sin(2*pi*(t+offset)/24))
  ts = pmin(pmax(ts,0),1)
  return(ts)
})}

timeSpentByHour_sin = function(offset=3, pwr=1, eps=0, mn=0.05, amp=1){
 params = list()
 class(params) <- "sin"
 params$offset = offset 
 params$pwr = pwr 
 params$eps = eps 
 params$mn = mn 
 params$amp = amp 
 return(params)
}
atHome = timeSpentByHour(1:24, timeSpentByHour_sin(6, 3, -0.8)) 
inside = timeSpentByHour(1:24, timeSpentByHour_sin(5, 3, -1.2, 0, 2))*atHome*0.98
inBed  = timeSpentByHour(1:24, timeSpentByHour_sin(4, 3, -1.2, 0, 3))*atHome*inside
plot(1:24, atHome, type = "l", ylim = range(0, 1), xlab = "Time of Day", ylab = "Relative Activity", xaxt="n")
lines(1:24, inside, col = "blue") 
lines(1:24, inBed, col = "red") 
axis(1, c(6, 12, 18, 22), c("6am", "noon", "6pm", "10pm"))

noon2noon = function(ftime, clr = "black", add=F){
  ix = c(13:24, 1:12)
  if(add==F) {
    plot(1:24, ftime[ix], type = "l", xaxt = "n", xlab = "Time of Day", ylab = "Relative Activity", col = clr)
    axis(1, c(6, 10, 18, 24), c("6pm", "10 pm", "6 am", "noon"))
  }
  if(add==T) lines(1:24, ftime[ix], col = clr) 
}
noon2noon(atHome)
noon2noon(inside, "blue", T)
noon2noon(inBed, "red", T)

Circadia

We let \(\xi(t)\) denote relative mosquito activity rates.

mozyBFActivityByHour = function(t,params){
  UseMethod("mozyBFActivityByHour", params)
}
mozyBFActivityByHour.sin = function(t, params){with(params,{
  crude = pmax(1+eps+sin(2*pi*(t+offset)/24),0) + mn
  return(crude/mean(crude))
})}

paramsBFActivityByHour_sin = function(offset=3, pwr=1, eps=0, mn=0.05){
 params = list()
 class(params) <- "sin"
 params$offset = offset 
 params$pwr = pwr 
 params$eps = eps 
 params$mn = mn 
 return(params)
}
circ1 = mozyBFActivityByHour(1:24, paramsBFActivityByHour_sin(3,3,-0.4))
circ2 = mozyBFActivityByHour(1:24, paramsBFActivityByHour_sin(5,3,-0.2))
noon2noon(circ1, "red")
noon2noon(circ2, "blue", T)
